			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2016</a> paper:</span><br><i>Xdiagram: A Declarative Textual DSL for Describing Diagram Editors (Tool Demo)</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AndreLuísdeMedeirosSantos.html">Andre Luís de Medeiros Santos</a>, <a href="../profile/EduardoGomes.html">Eduardo Gomes</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2997364.2997377">10.1145/2997364.2997377</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> Xdiagram is a DSL for specifying diagram editors for DSMLs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It is meant to generate/support tooling (diagram editors), i.e., meta-tooling for language workbenches.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL">T4F: Visualisation</span></a><ul><li> Its purpose is to define and realize graphical syntax/editors, directly tied to visualization.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It supports language design by enabling definition of concrete (diagrammatic) notations.
</li></ul></li></ul>
